'''''Planet of Twilight''''' is a [[Star Wars Legends|''Star Wars'' Legends]] novel written by [[Barbara Hambly]] and published by [[Bantam Spectra]] in [[April]] [[1997]]. It is the final volume of an informal [[Callista trilogy|trilogy]] involving ex–[[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] [[Callista Ming]]. The previous books in the cycle are [[Children of the Jedi (novel)|''Children of the Jedi'']] ([[1995]]), also by Hambly and ''[[Darksaber (novel)|Darksaber]]'' (1995) by [[Kevin J. Anderson]].

An [[Planet of Twilight (abridged audiobook)|audio version]] narrated by [[Anthony Heald]] was released in 2007.

==Publisher's summary==
''Nam Chorios is a barren backwater world&mdash;once a dreaded prison colony, now home to a fanatic religious cult. It is here that Princess Leia has been taken captive by a ruthless and charismatic warlord bent on destroying the New Republic. Meanwhile, Luke lands on a mysterious planet in search of his lost love, Callista, only to discover the Force is his own worst enemy. But worst of all, as Han, Chewie, and Lando leave Coruscant on a desperate rescue mission, a strange life-form, unlike any the galaxy has ever seen, awakens...a life-form so malevolent it will destroy everything&mdash;both Empire and New Republic&mdash;on its path to domination.''

==Plot summary==
The [[Rationalist Party]] of [[Nam Chorios/Legends|Nam Chorios]] asks the [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]] to intervene in the burgeoning conflict with the [[Planet/Legends|planet's]] traditional minded [[Theran Listener|Theran Listeners]], whose devotion to superstition and prohibitions against technology have kept the world cloistered from interstellar trade. Seven [[Standard century/Legends|centuries]] earlier, Nam Chorios was settled as a [[Prison/Legends|prison]] colony, with powerful gun stations meant to secure the skies. The fanatical [[Theran|Therans]] have commandeered these guns and use them to blast any large [[Starship/Legends|vessel]] on approach, dooming the world to isolation. Though [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia]] is personally sympathetic to the party's position and empathizes with its leader [[Seti Ashgad/Legends|Seti Ashgad]], she cannot intervene in this affair. After Ashgad visits Leia aboard her [[Flagship/Legends|flagship]] accompanied by his aide, [[Dzym]], and a pair of [[Humanoid/Legends|humanoid]] [[Synthdroid|synthdroid]] [[Bodyguard/Legends|bodyguards]], he knocks Leia unconscious and kidnaps her, taking her to Nam Chorios. The synthdroids unleash the [[Death Seed]] plague aboard the New Republic vessels, [[Death/Legends|killing]] all aboard. 

[[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] is drawn to Nam Chorios for other reasons. Prior to Leia's meeting with Ashgad, she had received a scrawled message of warning from [[Callista Ming|Callista]] to stay away. The former [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] had been to the world, prompting Luke to search for her there. Despite his cautious [[Pilot/Legends|piloting]], Luke's [[A/SF-01 B-wing starfighter/Legends|B-wing fighter]] is shot from the skies, and he crashes into the [[Crystal/Legends|crystalline]] landscape. It is a bleak setting, infested with [[Parasite/Legends|parasitic]] [[Droch/Legends|drochs]] – tiny [[Blood/Legends|bloodsucking]] [[Insect/Legends|insects]]. Despite this desolation, [[The Force/Legends|the Force]] flourishes, and Luke is alarmed at how powerful it is on Nam Chorios. Leia awakens within Ashgad's fortress and sees that his co-conspirators include Dzym, the [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitive]] [[Hutt/Legends|Hutt]] [[Beldorion|Beldorion the Splendid]], and the kindhearted programmer [[Liegeus Vorn]]. Vorn does what he can to make Leia's stay more comfortable, for he is very much a [[Prisoner/Legends|prisoner]] of the conspirators as well. 

Leia begins to piece together Ashgad’s plot, a complex web of alliances joined in parallel goals. Ashgad is spreading the Death Seed plague across the [[Meridian sector/Legends|Meridian sector]] to destabilize it. Backing Ashgad's plan is [[Moff/Legends|Moff]] [[Tol Getelles|Getelles]] of the adjacent [[Antemeridian sector/Legends|Antemeridian sector]], who intends to annex the Meridian. Ashgad also has the support of the [[Loronar Corporation/Legends|Loronar Corporation]], which seeks [[Mining/Legends|mineral]] rights on Nam Chorios. In exchange, the corporation has offered up automated [[Needle fighter|needle fighters]] that can be enhanced with Chorian crystals to Ashgad’s cause of destroying the stalwart Therans. Leia's kidnapping is part of an attempt to derail and deadlock the New Republic government. With the help of local settlers, Luke follows Callista's trail and confirms that she was once on the planet. He discovers that the so-called [[Tsil|Spook-crystals]] in the planet are [[Sentience/Legends|sentient]] transmitters and amplifiers of the Force. They are the source of the Therans' [[Force healing/Legends|supernatural healing]] abilities and deeply rooted spirituality. He also meets an aged Jedi, [[Taselda]], a member of the [[Jedi Order/Legends|old Order]] who has been kept alive by consuming drochs, though the hardships of Nam Chorios have stripped her of her reason. She claims to have trained Callista during her visit. Taselda tries to manipulate Luke into carrying out her dreams of vengeance against Beldorion, the Hutt who wounded her and [[Thief/Legends|stole]] [[Taselda's lightsaber|her lightsaber]]. 

Luke and Leia discover a more disturbing layer to the plot – the true mastermind of all this chaos. The tiny drochs are the source of the Death Seed plague, and one of their members – Dzym – has been mutated to the point of sentience. He scarcely resembles his [[Insectoid/Legends|insectoid]] origins. He has ambitions to take over [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]] by spreading the plague offworld. Ashgad and Beldorion are under his sway since Dzym offers them vitality and longevity through the transfer of [[Living Force/Legends|life energy]]. To succeed, Dzym needs a starship filled with drochs to escape Nam Chorios, past the gun stations. In their desperate race to stop Dzym, Leia must first defeat the corrupt Beldorian, which she does in a [[Lightsaber duel/Legends|lightsaber duel]] with her well-muscled larger foe. Through the Force, Luke compels the crystal-driven needle fighters to shoot down Ashgad's ship. Luke comes to understand that the crystals knew that the drochs were the source of the plague, and so – acting through the Therans – they purposely kept Nam Chorios isolated. 

Moff Getelles’ invasion fleet is thwarted by a New Republic task force arranged by [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]] and [[Lando Calrissian/Legends|Lando Calrissian]] and bolstered by a surprise ally: [[Admiral/Legends|Admiral]] [[Natasi Daala|Daala]]. She was disgusted with how low Getelles would stoop to secure territory and power. Daala's arrival happily reunites her with Liegeus Vorn, a former lover whom she hadn’t seen in [[Standard year/Legends|years]]. Luke is likewise reunited with Callista, who was captured by Ashgad in her attempt to stop him. The two have a wordless exchange, but each recognizes that their time together has come to an end. 

==Continuity==
The description of the plot on the inside flap of the hardcover misnamed [[Nam Chorios/Legends|Nam Chorios]] as Renat Chorios and [[Seti Ashgad/Legends|Seti Ashgad]] as Seti Draconis, the only place where those versions of these names appear.<ref name="TERC" /> 

